03851nam a22004935i 9780674058538DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20212010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740585387 a10.4159/97806740585382doi  a(DE-B1597)577689  a(OCoLC)1248760243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aD520.T8bM36 2010eb 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a940.3/12221 aMcMeekin, Sean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Berlin-Baghdad Express :bThe Ottoman Empire and Germany's Bid for World Power /cSean McMeekin. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (496 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps -- tList of Abbreviations -- tA Note on Names and Translations -- tPrologue: The View from Haydarpasha -- tI The Vision -- tII The Prophet Armed -- tIII Adventures in German Jihad -- tIV Boomerang -- tEpilogue: The Strange Death of German Zionism and the Nazi-Muslim Connection -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe modern Middle East was forged in the crucible of the First World War, but few know the full story of how war actually came to the region. As Sean McMeekin reveals in this startling reinterpretation of the war, it was neither the British nor the French but rather a small clique of Germans and Turks who thrust the Islamic world into the conflict for their own political, economic, and military ends. The Berlin–Baghdad Express tells the fascinating story of how Germany exploited Ottoman pan-Islamism in order to destroy the British Empire, then the largest Islamic power in the world. Meanwhile the Young Turks harnessed themselves to German military might to avenge Turkey’s hereditary enemy, Russia. Told from the perspective of the key decision-makers on the Turco-German side, many of the most consequential events of World War I—Turkey’s entry into the war, Gallipoli, the Armenian massacres, the Arab revolt, and the Russian Revolution—are illuminated as never before. Drawing on a wealth of new sources, McMeekin forces us to re-examine Western interference in the Middle East and its lamentable results. It is an epic tragicomedy of unintended consequences, as Turkish nationalists give Russia the war it desperately wants, jihad begets an Islamic insurrection in Mecca, German sabotage plots upend the Tsar delivering Turkey from Russia’s yoke, and German Zionism midwifes the Balfour Declaration. All along, the story is interwoven with the drama surrounding German efforts to complete the Berlin to Baghdad railway, the weapon designed to win the war and assure German hegemony over the Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aGeopoliticszGermanyxHistory. 0aJihad. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zIslamic countries. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zTurkey. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674058538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674058538.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles